definition.value: An organic iodide salt in which the cationic component is 1,3-dimethylimidazolium.
A six-membered glucosamine oligosaccharide consisting of two repeating units of beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)]-beta-D-GlcNAc joined by a (1->3)-linkage.
A 1-alkyl-3-methylimidazolium in which the alkyl substituent at C-1 is ethyl.
An organic chloride salt in which the cationic component is 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium.
alpha-L-Fucp-(1->2)-beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Fucp-(1->3)]-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Galp with configuration alpha at the anomeric centre of the galactose residue at the reducing end.

A furanochrome in which the basic tricyclic skeleton is substituted at positions 4 and 9 with methoxy groups and at position 7 with a methyl group. A major constituent of the plant Ammi visnaga it is a herbal folk medicine used for various illnesses, its main effect being as a vasodilator.
A C20, straight-chain, polyunsaturated fatty acid anion containing five double bonds.
The organosulfonate oxoanion that is the trianion of Reactive Blue 5, formed by loss of a proton from each of the sulfo groups; major species at pH 7.3.

A branched heptasaccharide derivative consisting of two repeating units of beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)]-beta-D-GlcNAc (joined by a (1->3)-linkage) with an alpha-L-fucosyl residue attached at the 2-position of the galactose residue at the non-reducing end.
A 1-alkyl-3-methylimidazolium in which the alkyl substituent at C-1 is butyl.
A branched amino pentasaccharide comprising one fucose, two galactose, one glucosamine and one glucose unit (at the reducing end), linked as shown.
An organic iodide salt in which the cationic component is 1-butyl-3-methylimidazolium.
A dicarboxylate that contains four carbon atoms.
A 1-alkyl-3-methylimidazolium in which the alkyl substituent at C-1 is hexyl.
A thiol that is the alpha-anomeric glycoside of L-cysteinyl-D-glucosamine with L-malic acid.
A phenolate anion that results from the removal of a proton from the hydroxy group at position 7 of 5-hydroxypseudobaptigenin.
An organic chloride salt in which the cationic component is 1-hexyl-3-methylimidazolium.
A 1-alkyl-3-methylimidazolium in which the alkyl substituent at C-1 is octyl.
An organic chloride salt in which the cationic component is 3-methyl-1-octylimidazolium.
A branched amino hexasaccharide made up from two fucose, two galactose, one glucosamine and one glucose unit (at the reducing end).
A sesquiterpene that is 1,1'-bi(cyclohexane)-1,3'-diene substituted at positions 4', 5, and 5 by methyl groups (the S- enantiomer).

A catechol-type siderophore with a structure of D-lysyl-L-serine substituted on N(2) of the lysyl residue by a 2,3-dihydroxybenzoyl group. It is produced by the Gram-negative bacillus Dickeya dadantii (previously known as Erwinia chrysanthem). Only the catecholate hydroxyl groups participate in metal coordination, so chrysobactin cannot provide full 1:1 coordination of Fe(III); at neutral pH and concentrations of about 0.1 mM, ferric chrysobactin exists as a mixture of bis and tris complexes.
A citrate siderophore possessing four carboxylate groups suitable for iron coordination.
A 1-alkyl-3-methylimidazolium in which the alkyl substituent at C-1 is decyl.
An organic chloride salt in which the cationic component is 1-decyl-3-methylimidazolium.
A 1-alkyl-3-methylimidazolium in which the alkyl substituent at C-1 is dodecyl.
An organic tetrafluoroborate salt in which the cationic component is 1-dodecyl-3-methylimidazolium.
An organic salt containing tetrafluoroborate as the anionic component.

A branched amino pentasaccharide consisting of D-glucose at the reducing end having an alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->3)-[beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl moiety attached at the 4-position.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly[2-(diisopropylamino)ethyl methacrylate] macromolecules.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly[2-(diethylamino)ethyl methacrylate] macromolecules.
Any hydroxy carboxylic acid which contains a hydroxy group located beta- to the carboxylic acid group.
A branched amino hexasaccharide comprising two fucose, two galactose, one glucosamine and one glucose unit (at the reducing end), linked as shown.
A linear amino pentasaccharide comprising one fucose, two galactose, one glucosamine and one glucose unit (at the reducing end), linked as shown.
An acryilic polymer, composed of poly(N-acryloxysuccinimide) macromolecules.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly(perylene bisimide acrylate) macromolecules.
Any glycosphingolipid where the oligosaccharide component has an N-acetylgalactosaminyl residue at the non-reducing end.
An ether in which the ethereal oxygen is derived from one of the hydroxy groups of a cyclitol.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly(butyl acrylate) macromolecules.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly[2-(acetoacetoxy)ethyl methacrylate] macromolecules.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly(sodium acrylate) macromolecules.
A tetradecenoic acid having its double bond in the 2-position.
A tetradecenoic acid having its double bond in the 7-position.
Organotin compounds in which the tin atom is bonded to a 2-hydroxybutyl group
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly(methyl methacrylate) macromolecules.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly(stearyl methacrylate) macromolecules.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly(ethyl methacrylate) macromolecules.
